The 1ct tw (0.5ct per ear) is where most buyers find the right balance. At approximately 4.7 × 3.3mm, the rectangular outline is clearly readable at normal distance. The step-cut details — the long parallel facet lines — are visible up close. The stone is present without being heavy.

The ½ct tw at approximately 3.6 × 2.5mm is more subtle. The shape still reads as an emerald cut, but the step-cut detail requires closer viewing. It is the right choice if you want something understated that you know is there — not something that announces itself. The ¾ct tw at 4.2 × 3.0mm lands between the two.

One practical note: ear lobe size affects how the stone reads. Smaller lobes make the same stone appear proportionally larger. Larger lobes may need 1ct tw or above for the stone to hold visual weight against the ear. The emerald cut's elongated shape helps at every size — horizontal spread always reads well at ear level regardless of lobe size.

